 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 {By choosing this move Black
accepts the possible damage of his pawn chain on the q-side.} 8. Bd3 {This
relatively quiet continuation isn't as harmless as it looks. It turns out,
that the extra h7-h6 (comparing to 6...Bf5) makes Black's setup less stable on
the k-side.} ({The more common} 8. Qf3 Bh7 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 {leads
to a long positional struggle when Black's bishop pair partly compensates for
his structural drawbacks. For instance,} 11. Kd2 Nd7 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Kxd3 Rg8
14. g3 f5 $1 {As was recently proved by GM Dmitry Andreikin, White struggles
to make progress on any side of the board.}) 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 ({The other
way of development makes a little sense:} 9... Nbd7 10. Nge2 Bd6 (10... Be7 {
transposes to the main line.}) 11. f3 O-O 12. e4 {White feels free to
immediately take the upper hand in the centre. Now the pinned Nf6 causes Black
certain problems.} dxe4 13. fxe4 Be7 14. Rd1 $14 {White's advantage is
undeniable due to his strong pawn centre. Sciarretta,R - Pintonello,G IECG
email 2008}) 10. Nge2 Nbd7 ({Black can also try to simplify the matters by
means of} 10... Ne4 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxe4 dxe4 {, but after} 13. Qb3 $1 {
Black struggles to develop his knight. For instance,} O-O 14. O-O Na6 15. f3 $1
{White exploits the poor placement of Na6 and starts and intense attack on the
f-file.} exf3 16. Rxf3 Qb4 17. Qc2 $14 {White's mobile central pawns are
supported by active rooks, so Black's position is dangerous. Meissner, B - Voss,
H Passau 1998}) (10... O-O 11. f3 Nbd7 {is another possible moves order.}) 11.
f3 {There is no need to delay this move - this is an important part of White's
central strategy.} O-O 12. O-O Re8 ({Too passive is} 12... Ne8 13. Bxe7 Qxe7
14. e4 $14 {Tan,R-Kirk,J Dos Hermanas 2004}) ({In case of} 12... Qb6 13. Kh1
Rae8 {Koudinov,D - Pliester,L Bussum 2011} {I suggest} 14. a4 $5 $146 ({
Instead, the straightforward} 14. e4 {runs into} Nxe4 $1 15. Bxe7 Nxc3 16. Bxf8
Nxe2 {Black will have a sufficient play for an exchange.}) {The annoying
threat of a4-a5 practically forces Black to play} 14... a5 {, and then} 15. e4
$36 {is more effective, since} Nxe4 16. Bxe7 Nxc3 {now is well met by} 17. Bc5
$1 Nxc5 18. dxc5 Qxb2 19. Nxc3 $16) 13. Bf2 {The bishop did its job on the
h4-d8 diagonal, and now White retreats it to take more control of d4.} Bd6 (
13... c5 {took place in the classical game Botvinnik, M-Geller,E Moscow 1955} {
My natural improvement over that game is} 14. Rad1 $146 cxd4 ({After} 14... c4
15. Qc2 $36 {White's further extension in the centre overwhelms Black's play
on the q-side.}) 15. Nxd4 Ne5 16. Qb5 $14 {The pressure on the isolated Pd5 is
strong enough.}) 14. Ng3 Re6 {This position was reached in Wojtaszek, R - Stern,
R Germany 2022} ({The ambitious} 14... h5 15. Rae1 Bc7 16. Kh1 Re6 {took place
in the corr game Egorov, V - Filak, R LSS email 2016} {In my opinion, White
could have claimed the drawbacks of it with} 17. Nge2 $1 $146 Rc8 ({After} 
17... Qe7 18. Ng1 Re8 19. Nh3 $36 {the threat of Ng5 is very annoying.}) 18. Bh4
Qe8 19. Nf4 Bxf4 20. exf4 $14 {Black's knights are well restricted, and the
king is quite exposed.}) 15. Rae1 $146 Qc7 {It looks like Black manages to pin
the Ng3 and harmoniously place his pieces,} ({In the event of} 15... Rc8 16.
Kh1 c5 {White can successfully switch to fight against the isolated pawn:} 17.
Nf5 Bf8 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Qb1 $14 {Black is under long-lasting pressure.}) {
but the strong} 16. Nf5 $1 {interrupts his plans:} Bxh2+ {Black wins a pawn,
but it costs him wasting a tempo.} ({After} 16... Rae8 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. Qc2
Qe7 19. Ne2 $14 {White will transfer his knight on d3 and try to grab space on
the q-side with b2-b4, a2-a4 e.t.c, while Black can only sit and wait.}) 17.
Kh1 Bd6 18. e4 {As a result, White makes a strong pawns centre.} dxe4 19. fxe4
Nh7 {Black has to move his pieces back to avoid the material losses.} 20. e5
Bf8 21. Ne2 $36 {The activity of pieces offers White more than full
compensation.} *

