 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O ({Another setup is connected
with keeping the king in the centre for a while:} 7... h6 8. Bh4 Be6 {, but
the Be6 is placed rather awkwardly and white can claim it with the energetic}
9. f4 $1 g5 10. fxg5 Nh7 ({After} 10... Ne4 11. Qh5 Qd7 12. g6 {Black was
nearly lost in Delemarre,J-Vermulst,M Hengelo 1992}) 11. Qb3 hxg5 12. Bg3 $36 {
White has the more harmonious position (especially in view of poor Nh7), and
Black has no comfortable way to cover b7.}) 8. Nge2 h6 (8... Re8 9. Qc2 h6 10.
Bh4 {is another possible moves order.}) 9. Bh4 Re8 10. Qc2 a5 {This
interesting approach became rather popular in recent years. Black makes it
tougher for White to start the ''minority attack'' with b2-b4. Also, by
playing 10...a5 Black vacates a6 for his knight.} (10... Nbd7 {gets us back
to 6...Bd6 & Nbd7 Chapter.}) ({The solid} 10... Be6 {, intending to
harmoniously complete development with ...Nbd7 can be well met by} 11. f3 $1 ({
But not} 11. O-O $2 Bxh2+ 12. Kxh2 Ng4+ 13. Kg3 g5 {with a stunning attack.})
11... c5 ({In case of} 11... Nbd7 12. O-O Qc7 {Campbell,I - Jenneborg,S LSS
email 2019} {White should have played the simple} 13. h3 $1 $36 {, and then
the ..e3-e4 break in inventable.}) 12. Nb5 Bf8 {This position occurred in Fier,
A - Ynojosa Aponte, F Batumi 2018} {White should have accepted the gambit:} 13.
dxc5 $146 Nc6 ({Or} 13... Nbd7 14. Nd6 Qa5+ 15. Qc3 $14) 14. Nd6 $1 {It's a
good moment for converting the extra pawn into a better pawn structure.} Bxd6
15. cxd6 Qxd6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Qd2 $14 {Black has no full compensation for
his structural drawbacks.}) (10... b6 {is mostly played with an idea of
exchanging the light-squared bishops} 11. h3 Ba6 (11... Nbd7 12. O-O Bb7 {
leads to the position, that was covered in the Chapter with 6...Bd6 & 7...Nbd7.
}) 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O Nb8 {Black achieved his goal, but it costs him losing
a few tempi. This was Halldorsson, J - Sigurjonsson, S Reykjavik 2018} {In my
opinion, White should have slowly increased the pressure with} 14. Rac1 $146
Nbd7 15. Qd3 Rc8 16. Rc2 $14) ({Dubious is} 10... Bg4 $6 {Tran,T - Savchenko,B
Moscow 2019} {White can prove, that the Bg4 has no good prospects with
energetic} 11. f3 $1 Bh5 12. g4 $1 Bg6 13. Bxg6 fxg6 14. Bf2 $36 {Black's king
feels very exposed.}) 11. h3 Na6 {The most consistent. Black threatens 12...
Nb4, but the main idea is transferring the knight to e6 via c7.} ({The
alternative} 11... b6 12. O-O Ba6 13. Rac1 {leads to a long strategic struggle
when White has a slight, but stable positional advantage because of weak Pc6:}
Bxd3 14. Qxd3 a4 (14... Nbd7 15. Rc2 b5 16. Rfc1 $14) 15. a3 Nbd7 16. Rc2 b5
17. Na2 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence in Evans,G - Brewer,S ICCF
email 2011}) 12. a3 {White has to spend a tempo for prophylactics.} Nc7 13. O-O
Ne6 {This complex position was tested many times on the high level, when
Black's side includes Magnus Carlsen.} ({Too passive is} 13... Bd7 14. Rae1 Be7
{This looks like a clear concession.} 15. Bg3 Rc8 16. Be5 Be6 17. Nf4 $14 {
Lenderman,A - Xiong,J Saint Louis 2021}) 14. Rad1 {This is only White's 3rd
choice by statistics, but I find this move the most flexible.} ({The aggressive
} 14. f4 {is nicely met by} Be7 $1 {, and then} 15. Ng3 $6 g5 16. fxg5 hxg5 17.
Nf5 gxh4 {didn't yield White sufficient compensation for a piece in Dubov, D
- Xiong,J Chess.com INT 2022}) (14. f3 $5 {is worth attention either, although
Black scores well after it.}) 14... Bd7 {This is the most challenging move for
White: Black develops the bishop and makes c8 vacant for his heavy piece.} (
14... Ng5 15. f4 Ne6 {was seen in Kashlinskaya,A - Rosen,E Chess.com INT 2020}
({After} 15... Nxh3+ 16. gxh3 Rxe3 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Bf5 $16 {Black has only 2
pawns for the piece, and White's king is safe.}) {Here White can choose
between a few good-looking possibilities, but I mostly like the energetic} 16.
Ng3 $146 Nf8 17. e4 dxe4 18. Ngxe4 Be7 {This passive retreat is necessary.} 19.
Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. d5 $36 {The lack of development makes Black's
position highly unpleasant.}) 15. e4 $5 $146 {This ambitious continuation
isn't without strategic risk: White is left with an isolated pawn.} ({The usual
} 15. f3 {runs into} Ng5 $1 16. f4 ({Worse is} 16. e4 $2 Nfxe4 17. fxe4 Nxh3+
18. gxh3 Qxh4 $17 {Ringoir,T - Korley,K Charlotte 2019}) 16... Nxh3+ 17. gxh3
Rxe3 18. Bf5 Qc8 $1 $44 {Now the point of Bc8-d7 becomes obvious: Black has a
promising play for a piece.}) 15... dxe4 ({After} 15... g5 $6 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17.
fxg3 dxe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 {The control over f-file offers White a
strong attack.}) 16. Nxe4 Be7 {This is the only way to release the pressure on
the Nf6.} 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd6 {This is the point of White's 15th move. The
strong Nd6 seems to bother Black and restrict the mobility of his pieces.} Re7
({After} 18... Rf8 19. Bc4 Qb6 20. Ne4 $1 Be7 21. N2g3 $36 {The activity of
knights also feels quite annoying for the second player.}) 19. Bc4 $1 Qc7 ({
In case of} 19... Be8 20. Nf5 Rd7 21. Rfe1 {there is nothing concrete yet, but
Black's position seems very dangerous.}) 20. Ne4 $1 {it turns out, that the
Bf6 is in danger.as well.} Bg5 21. g3 {The threat of 22.h4 is very annoying,
so Black has serious problems to solve.} *

