 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
c6 6. e3 Bd6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Nge2 O-O ({The idea of saving a tempo on further ..
.Re8 costs Black leaving his king in the centre. Still, it is a common guest
on GM's level.} 8... Nf8 9. f3 $1 {This energetic move is the best way to
claim the drawbacks of Black's manoeuvre.} Ng6 {An ambitious idea: now there is
no good square for retreating the Bg5, and Black wants to play ...h7-h6.} ({
In case of} 9... Ne6 10. Bh4 O-O 11. Qc2 g6 12. O-O {Black suffers from the nasty
pin, so there is hardly anything better than} Be7 13. Rae1 Ng7 {This was
Rivera, I - Ortegon Villacorte, L Quibdo 2015} {Here White has no reason for
deviating from the most natural} 14. e4 $146 dxe4 15. fxe4 Be6 16. h3 $16 {
with a clear advantage.}) 10. Qc2 h6 {The most consistent. Black is interested
in neutralizing the strong dark-squared bishop of the opponent.} ({After} 10... O-O
$146 {White can quickly extend his initiative on the k-side with} 11. h4 $1 h6
12. h5 Ne7 13. Bh4 $36) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. O-O {The threat of 13.e4 practically
forces Black to waste a tempo for moving his queen.} Qh4 13. g3 Qg5 {we have
been following Musialkiewicz, J - Chmielarz, M (Borowice 2012} {White could have
claimed the drawbacks of opponent's setup by means of} 14. f4 $1 $146 Qg4 15.
f5 Ne7 16. e4 $40 {Black's queen is nearly trapped, and the king is still in
the centre.}) 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bh4 Re8 11. h3 $1 {By making this vital White
prepares a short castle. Also, in some cases White can push ..g2-g4, since the
Ph6 is a sort of target for an attack.} ({The aggressive} 11. O-O-O {is well
met by} b5 $1 12. g4 b4 13. Na4 Nb6 $132 {Black's attacking prospects were by
no means inferior. Polak,T - Druska,J Blansko 2019}) ({The careless} 11. O-O $2
{meets} Bxh2+ $1 12. Kxh2 Ng4+ 13. Kg3 Ndf6 $1 {with a powerful attack.}) 11...
Nf8 ({The alternative way of development -} 11... b5 12. O-O {creates
weaknesses on the q-side. The play might continue:} Bb7 ({After} 12... a5 13.
Rac1 Ba6 14. Rfd1 Qb8 15. Bg3 {Black didn't have compensation for a weak Pc6.
Csernus,R - Kolanek,S LSS email 2017}) 13. Bh7+ $146 {Before placing the
bishop on f5 it makes sense to interrupt the natural setup of Black.} Kh8 14.
Bf5 {Threatening to damage Black's pawn chain with ..Bxd7} Nb6 15. b3 {Now
Black's counter-attacking abilities are limited.} a5 16. Nb1 b4 17. Nd2 $14 {
White has both the superior pawn structure and the more active pieces.}) ({
Too passive seems} 11... b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rac1 Qe7 {Martinez Pinares,K -
Solovyov,V ICCF email 2018} {Now I mostly like the natural} 14. Ng3 $146 Bb8
15. Nf5 Qf8 16. e4 $36 {Most of Black's pieces are placed awkwardly, so White
benefits from opening the e-file.}) 12. O-O {The safest and the best.} ({After
} 12. O-O-O a5 13. g4 b5 {Black had an excellent counter-play against Kc1 in
Petrosyan,M - Kramnik,V Moscow 2019}) 12... Bd7 {Black is aiming to connect
this rooks as soon as it possible.} (12... Ne6 {, intending to spot the knight
on g5 is well met by} 13. Rad1 Ng5 (13... Bd7 14. f3 Ng5 15. f4 Ne6 16. Ng3 {
leads to approximately the same. hardly the extra Bc8-d7 move might help Black
to solve the space issues.}) 14. f4 $1 Ne6 ({After} 14... Nxh3+ $2 15. gxh3
Bxh3 16. Rf3 Bg4 17. Rg3 $18 {White has a material advantage and the safer
king!}) 15. Ng3 Nc7 16. Qe2 $14 {Black spent a few tempi by moving his knight,
and now White has excellent attacking prospects on the k-side. Stronsky, V -
Rogos,J ICCF email 2012}) 13. Rae1 Rc8 {This position occurred in Benno, P - Gal,
G Hungary 2005} {In my opinion, White could have exploited the pinned Nf6 with}
14. e4 g5 {Black cannot do without this committing advance - the pin is too
annoying.} 15. Bg3 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 $14 {The vulnerability of Kg8
puts Black under long-termed pressure.} *

