 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {This moves order gained
popularity in the recent years. As we will see, the Nb8 might be also placed
on a6 in some cases.} 8. Nge2 {It makes sense to keep the queen on its initial
spot for a while.} ({The most popular} 8. Qc2 h6 9. Bh4 Re8 10. Nge2 {can be
well met by} a5 $5 11. O-O Na6 12. a3 Nc7 {, and then Black is prepared for
well for the standard confrontation in the centre:} 13. f3 c5 $1 {As was
proved in practice, Black has sufficient play along the e-file.}) 8... Re8 ({
Starting with} 8... h6 9. Bh4 {usually has no independent character. For
instance,} Ne4 (9... Re8 {is another possible moves order.}) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11.
Bxe4 {White liquidates the only active piece of the opponent. From now the Pe4 is
a cause of worries.} dxe4 12. Qc2 Bf5 (12... f5 13. Nf4 Qf7 {occured in Sedlak,
N - Bergez,L Lienz 2011} {Here I suggest} 14. f3 $5 $146 exf3 15. gxf3 $36 {
White has excellent attacking prospects on the g-file. Obviously, Black
would have prefered to get his pawn back on h7.}) 13. O-O Nd7 14. d5 $1 {
White will either have the strong d-passer or damage the opponent's pawn chain.
} Rad8 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Nd4 {Black was positionally busted in Abdusattorov, N
- Van Foreest, J Warsaw 2021}) (8... Ne4 {This attempt to simplify the matters
can be well met by} 9. Bf4 $1 {This position was tested in some correspondence
games, but it definitely cannot be acceptable for the second player. Now the
