 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {A flexible continuation.
In most cases Black castles next, so there are many possible transpositions.
However, by keeping the king in the centre Black acquires some additional
possibilities.} 8. Qc2 {A flexible continuation. White can decide where to
spot his king's knight later.} ({In particular, by starting with} 8. Nge2 {
White allows the immediate knight's transfer to e6:} Nf8 $5 9. Qc2 Ne6 10. Bh4
g6 11. O-O (11. O-O-O Bd7 12. h3 Rc8 13. Kb1 O-O $132 {Timofeev,A - Sjugirov,S
Yaroslavl 2019}) 11... O-O 12. f3 b5 {The practical tests prove, that Black's
counter-chances shouldn't be underestimated.}) 8... Nf8 $6 {In my opinion,
this move is dubious, although it was played by many strong players, such
Ipatov, Lu shaglei,Martirosyan and other GM's.} (8... Nb6 {might transpose to
8...Nh5 in case of 9.Nge2, but White has a decent alternative option:} 9. Nf3
$5 {In this redaction White's knight can be comfortably placed in the centre.}
Nh5 ({After} 9... h6 10. Bh4 Be6 11. O-O O-O 12. Ne5 {it is getting obvious,
that the nd7 moved too early. For instance,} Nfd7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. f4 Nxe5 15.
dxe5 $36 {Black's king got under strong attack in Luz, A - Santana Magalhaes, A
Florianopolis 2019}) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O g6 12. Rab1 {This time the minority
attack seems to be more annoying for Black than in the other Carlsbad lines.}
O-O 13. b4 a6 14. a4 Be6 (14... Bg4 {, as in Moskalenko,V - Pavlovic,M
Hoogeveen 2010} {also can be well met by} 15. Nd2 $146 Ng7 16. a5 Nd7 17. Rfe1
{Now, when White made maximum progress on the q-side it makes sense to start
the usual extension in the centre} Bf5 18. e4 dxe4 19. Ndxe4 $14 {Black is
under long-termed pressure because of passive pieces and weak Pb7.}) 15. Nd2 ({
Of course, not} 15. b5 $2 cxb5 16. axb5 a5 $15 {, and Black takes the upper
hand due to his strong passer.}) 15... Ng7 16. a5 Nc8 {Czakon,J - Bruzon
Batista,L Barbera del Valles 2008} {Here I suggest} 17. f3 $1 $146 {This time
this standard move is mainly aimed for preventing the unfavourable exchange of
bishops.} (17. Na4 Bf5 $11) 17... Nd6 ({Worse is} 17... Bf5 $6 18. e4 dxe4 19.
fxe4 Be6 20. Na4 $16) 18. Na4 Rae8 19. Rbe1 f5 20. Nc5 $14 {The knight has
reached its perfect outpost. Black is doomed to passive defence.}) ({Premature
seems} 8... g6 {Among the promising possibilities I mostly like the aggressive}
9. h4 $5 Nh5 {Matthai,E-Philipp,G DDR 1977} ({After} 9... Nf8 10. O-O-O Ne6 11.
Kb1 Nxg5 12. hxg5 Nh5 {, as in Colin, V - Grigorian, R Avoine 2016} {White can
claim a big advantage by means of} 13. f4 Ng3 14. Rh2 $16 {Black is
undeveloped, and the Ke8 is under attack.}) ({Hardly more attractive is} 9...
O-O 10. Nh3 b5 11. Nf4 $40 {with a direct attack.}) {, and now I see nothing
wrong with a straightforward} 10. g4 $146 Bxg5 11. hxg5 Qxg5 (11... Ng7 12. f4
$16) 12. gxh5 Qg2 {Black regain material, but after} 13. Be4 $1 dxe4 14. Qxe4+
Qxe4 15. Nxe4 $14 {White has an undeniable positional advantage due to his
strong pawns centre and more active pieces.}) 9. O-O-O $1 {I believe, this is
the most promising way of handling the position. Since Nd7-f8 is already
played, it is tougher for Black to make his counter-play with ...c6-c5.} ({
The quieter alternative -} 9. Nf3 Ne6 10. Bh4 g6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 {offers
White a very slight advantage. Mostly, Black manages to withstand the minority
attack after} Ng7 13. b4 a6 14. a4 Bf5) 9... Ne6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. f4 $1 {
A decent approach: the Ne6 is clearly misplaced now, and e5 is vacant for the
Ng1.} g6 ({In the event of} 11... Nc7 {I mostly like the prophylactic} 12. Re1
$1 (12. Nf3 Bg4 {seems less clear.}) 12... h6 13. Nf3 Bg4 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5
$16 {It is hard to withstand the storm of White's pawns. Livaic, L - Zupe, M
Skopje 2018}) 12. Nf3 Ng7 13. h3 {White is aiming to squeeze Black on the
k-side with g2-g4.} Bf5 14. g4 Bxd3 15. Rxd3 Be7 ({After} 15... O-O 16. Kb1 Re8
17. g5 Be7 18. Ne5 $16 {Black is very crumped, and the Kg8 is in permanent
danger.}) 16. Kb1 Qd6 17. Re1 O-O {We have been following Eljanov, P - Lu, S
China 2018} {White could have claimed his superiority with} 18. e4 $1 $146 Qxf4
19. exd5 Bd6 20. Re4 {with nearly a decisive advantage.} *

