 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 h6 8. Bh4 O-O (8... Nbd7 9.
Nge2 Nh5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc2 {is a transposition to the main
line.}) 9. Nge2 Nbd7 10. Qc2 Nh5 {Black is aiming to simplify the position,
even though it costs his placing his knight rather awkwardly. This approach is
a favourite weapon of legendary GM Michael Adams.} ({In case of} 10... Ne8 {
White can favorably deviate from trading the bishops with} 11. Bg3 $1 ({
Less promising is} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O Ndf6 13. Ng3 h5 $132 {Halliwell,T -
Pino Munoz,F ICCF email 2013}) 11... Bd6 {This is the only way to justify the
awkward Nf6-e8.} 12. O-O Bxg3 ({Hardly better is} 12... Ndf6 13. f3 Bxg3 14.
Nxg3 Nd6 15. Rad1 $14 {White is ready to push ..e3-e4 soon. Mesias Rojas, R -
Azevedo Junior,J Praia da Pipa 2014}) 13. Nxg3 Nd6 14. Rae1 Nf6 15. f3 $14 {
White's pieces are placed more harmoniously, and ..e3-e4 is to follow.
Soszynski, M - Daskal, Y ICCF email 2015}) (10... b5 {is a standard but quite
committing way of handling the position in Carlsbad. after all, c6 is a
permanent weakness.} 11. O-O a5 ({After} 11... Nb6 12. a4 a6 13. Bg3 {the Nb6
turns misplaced. It can be seen in the following line:} Bb7 $2 14. axb5 cxb5
15. Nxb5 {with 16.Bc7 to follow. White was winning in Wei, Y - Ju, W Xinghua 2021
}) ({Another natural way is} 11... Bb7 12. Rac1 Re8 13. h3 {A decent
prophylactic move - it secures g3 for the bishop and restricts the opponent's
knight.} a5 14. Bg3 Rc8 15. Bf5 $14 {1-0 (48) Hildebrand,G (2338)-Zawadka,Z 
(2194) ICCF email 2015}) 12. Rac1 {The most natural reaction on Black's last
move - White focuses on attacking the weak pawn.} Ba6 (12... Bb7 13. h3 Re8 14.
Bg3 {transposes to 11....Bb7}) 13. h3 {Since Black is well-prepared for the
traditional f2-f3, so White switches to a long positional play.} a4 14. a3 {
Fixing a favourable pawn structure.} Re8 (14... Nb6 {meets} 15. e4 $1 $14 {
, and the knight doesn't reach c4.}) 15. Na2 {A decent manoeuvre - White claims
the drawback of ...a5-a4 advance.} Bb7 16. Nb4 Bxb4 17. axb4 Nb6 {The natural
play by both sides led to this position in Hulse, P - Grummitt, W ICCF email 2012
} {White could have claimed superiority by means of} 18. Ra1 $1 $146 Nc4 19.
Nc1 $1 {there are great prospects for this knight!} Qe7 20. b3 axb3 21. Nxb3
$14) (10... b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rad1 Re8 {This position will be covered in
another Chapter from the next Database.}) (10... Re8 11. O-O {is a big line,
that will be also discussed in the second Database.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O ({
the more aggressive approach} 12. g4 $5 Nhf6 13. Rg1 Re8 14. O-O-O Ne4 {
leads to a complex, double-edged play.}) 12... Nb6 13. Rae1 Bd7 ({The same
manoeuvre might be effective also after} 13... Be6 14. Nc1 Rad8 15. Nb3 f5 {
Black takes more control of e4, but also weakens e5.} (15... Rfe8 16. Nc5 Bc8 {
transposes to the main line.}) 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. Be2 $1 {White immediately
exploits the weakness of e5-spot.} Nf6 18. Nd3 $14 {Sokolov,I - Thorfinnsson,B
Akureyri 2019}) 14. Nc1 {This was proved to be the most promising setup for
White - the knight is heading on c5, while e3 is covered by the rook now, so
f2-f3 is possible.} Rae8 (14... Rad8 15. Nb3 Rfe8 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. Ne2 ({
The straightforward} 17. b4 Nc4 $1 18. Qe2 Qg5 {was fine for Black in Navara, D
- Adams,M Biel 2015}) 17... Nd7 18. Nxd7 Bxd7 19. Rb1 Nf6 20. b4 Ne4 21. a4 {
Ghosh, A - Andersen, J ICCF email 2017}) ({It makes a little sense to retreat
the knight at once:} 14... Nf6 15. Nb3 Rad8 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. b4 a6 18. a4 $14 {
White managed to quickly extend on the Chatalbashev, B - Nielsen, V Denmark 2019}
) 15. Nb3 Nc8 {A decent manoeuvre - d6 is a great square for the knight.
However, it takes a few tempi to reach.} ({The other sensible idea is} 15... Qg5
{The active Qg5 puts White's king under definite pressure, so White has to
play accurately.} 16. a4 $1 $146 {I like this active move. White grabs space
on the q-side and forces Black to solve some concrete problems.} ({The
straighforward} 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. b4 {Chatalbashev,B - Cederstam Barsk,C
Sarpsborg 2019} {is less effective in view of} Nc4 $1 18. b5 cxb5 19. Nxb5 b6
$132 {with mutual chances.}) 16... Bc8 ({After} 16... Nc4 17. f4 Qh4 18. Bxc4
dxc4 19. Nd2 b5 20. Nf3 $36 {White's strong central pawns overweight Black's
passers.}) 17. f4 $1 {Black's knights are misplaced, so White can afford
weakening e4.} Qe7 18. a5 Nd7 (18... Nc4 19. e4 $16) 19. Nd2 $1 {It turns out,
that the Nb3 can be easily relocated to e5. Black is unable to cover this
square by means of ...f7-f6.} Nhf6 (19... Qb4 {runs into} 20. g4 Nhf6 21. g5
$40 {with a powerful attack. Black's queen is too far away from the king.}) 20.
Qa4 a6 21. Nf3 $14 {Black lacks any counter-attacking ideas and is doomed to
passive defence.}) 16. Nc5 Nd6 17. Qd1 $1 {I find this the most precise. Now
any way of defending the Nh5 has its drawbacks.} g6 $146 {This move is the
most challenging for White: Black keeps the Pf7 unblocked, so it's tougher for
White to make a strong pawn centre.} (17... Nf6 18. f3 $16 {was clearly better
for White in Aditya,M - Kozak,A Moscow 2020}) 18. Qa4 {White creates a double
threat: the Pd5 is also hanging.} ({Less accurate is} 18. f3 Bc8 19. e4 Nf4 20.
Bb1 Qg5 $132) 18... Bf5 19. Be2 $1 ({But not} 19. Bxf5 Nxf5 20. Qxa7 Nxd4 $1 {
, and Black is fine.}) 19... Qg5 20. Bxh5 Qxh5 21. f3 $14 {The poor placement
of Qh5 and the hanging Pa7 make Black's position uncomfortable.} *

