 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3
Nbd7 8. Qc2 Nh5 {In recent years this approach became very popular: Black
forces the favourable exchange of bishops, so the Qe7 will make it tougher to
push ..f2-f3. On the downside, the Nh5 is temporarily misplaced.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7
10. Nge2 ({Another ambitious continuation is} 10. O-O-O Nb6 11. h3 g6 12. Nf3
Be6 13. Kb1 O-O-O {This position was tested in dozens of high-level games, and
Black's position was proved to be solid enough.}) 10... g6 {The most common
choice. Black vacates g7 for his knight in order to exchange the bishops. Also,
by blocking the diagonal Black makes it possible to castle.} ({The immediate
knight's retreat feels like a clear concession:} 10... Nhf6 11. O-O O-O 12.
Rae1 Nb6 13. Nf4 {This is the point! Since Black moves his knight White is
able play this active move instead of 13.Nc1} Bd7 14. g3 $1 {A deep
prophylactic move. White secures g2 for a possible knight's retreat.} ({
Premature is} 14. f3 g5 $1 15. Nh3 Bxh3 16. gxh3 Rae8 $132 {with a balanced
play.}) 14... Qd6 ({Somewhat more natural looks} 14... Rac8 15. f3 {, but also
then after} c5 16. Qd2 cxd4 17. exd4 Qb4 18. Qf2 $14 {the symmetric pawn
structure doesn't guarantee Black equality - White's pieces are placed more
harmoniously, and the Pd5 is weaker than Pd4.}) 15. f3 Rfc8 ({The careless} 
15... c5 $2 16. dxc5 Qxc5 {runs into} 17. Ncxd5 $1 Qxc2 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Bxc2
$18) 16. g4 $1 {Stability in the centre makes it possible for White to extend
on the k-side.} g6 {This position occured in Leko,P - Naiditsch,A Dortmund 2014
} {Now the energetic} 17. h4 $1 $146 c5 18. Qh2 cxd4 19. exd4 $36 {,
threatening 20.Nfxd5 would have posed Black serious problems.}) (10... Nb6 11.
O-O g6 {leads to transposition.}) 11. O-O O-O (11... Ndf6 12. Rae1 O-O {
is another possible moves order.} ({Riskier is} 12... Ng7 13. Ng3 O-O 14. f3 h5
{Tarasova, V - Khomeriki, N Lichess.org INT 2020} {White should have continued:}
15. Qd2 $146 h4 16. Nge2 Re8 17. e4 $36 {, and Black finds himself
overextended.})) (11... Nb6 12. Rae1 O-O {is covered below.}) 12. Rae1 {
This move demonstrates, that White is fully focused on the extension in the
centre.} ({The minority attack, that starts with} 12. Rab1 a5 13. a3 {sin't so
promising. For instance,} Re8 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 b5 $1 $11 {The Pb4 is
equally weak as the Pc6. Fantinel,T - Siffert,A Europe Echecs INT 2021}) 12...
Ndf6 (12... f5 {This radical way of preventing ..e3-e4 was seen in dozens of
games. Here I present the following new idea:} 13. Nb1 $5 $146 {White's knight
immediately heads towards e5. It is a long way, but in such closed position
tempi are less valuable.} Ndf6 ({After} 13... Nhf6 14. Nd2 a5 15. Nf4 $14 {
it is only a matter of time before White will occupy the e5-spot.}) 14. Nd2 Be6
15. Nf3 $14 {Black's position appears solid but rather passive.}) ({Another
common choice is} 12... Nb6 13. Qd2 $5 {For some reason, this interesting move
is practically unexplored. At the same time, as 13.Nc1 it covers e3 and makes
it possible to play f2-f3.} ({This time} 13. Nc1 {is less impressive in view of
} Ng7 14. f3 Bf5 $1 {Black bravely provokes e3-e4} 15. e4 Be6 16. exd5 (16. e5
f6 17. f4 fxe5 18. fxe5 Qg5 {offers white no advantage.}) 16... Nxd5 $11 {
Wang,H - Sargissian,G Huaian 2016}) 13... Re8 ({Too passive is} 13... Nf6 14.
Ng3 Be6 15. f3 $16 {Mize,D - Bullen,A Lichess.org INT 2020}) (13... Bd7 {
This was Inarkiev,E - Duda,J Wroclaw 2014} {Here my natural new idea is} 14. e4
$5 $146 {White is trying to take advantage of opposition along the e-file and
some weakness of dark squares around the opponent's king.} dxe4 15. Nxe4 Rae8
16. N2g3 {The threat of 17.Nc5 is rather annoying. The activity of pieces more
than compensates for the isolated Pd4.}) 14. Nc1 Be6 ({In comparison to} 14...
Ng7 15. f3 Bf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. e4) 15. f3 Rad8 16. Qf2) 13. Nc1 {A deep idea:
White's plan involves f2-f3, Qc2-f2.} ({Too simplistic is} 13. Ng3 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Qd6 {Black is fine, as he manages
to prevent the nasty ..e3-e4.}) 13... b6 {A typical approach for such
positions: the c6-c5 advance is Black's key weapon in the further
confrontation.} (13... Be6 14. f3 b6 15. Qf2 c5 {leas to the position, that is
covered below.}) (13... Ng7 14. f3 c5 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Nb3 Qb6 17. Nd4 Ne6 18.
Qb3 Qxb3 ({The endgame, that arises after} 18... Nxd4 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. exd4
Be6 21. Kf2 {is highly unpleasant for Black because of permanent weaknesses on
the q-side.}) 19. Nxb3 Rd8 20. Rd1 b6 21. Rd2 {White's play is natural and
strong - there is a massive attack on the Pd5.} Bb7 22. Bc2 Rac8 23. Rfd1 $14 {
Black had to struggle hard for a draw till end of the game. Oparin, G - Grachev,
B Jerusalem 2015}) 14. f3 c5 15. Qf2 {The presence of queen on the k-side
should increase the attacking potential.} Bb7 {The most natural way of
development.} ({After} 15... Be6 {White can quickly extend his initiative on
the k-side with} 16. g4 $5 Ng7 17. N1e2 Rad8 18. Nf4 cxd4 19. exd4 $14 {
The opposition along the e-file was quite annoying for Black in Real de Azua, E
- Valerga,D Buenos Aires 2015}) 16. Rd1 {White isn't going to play e3-e4 any
soon, so it makes sense to move the Rf1.} c4 {The most challenging move for
White - the pawn majority on the q-side shouldn't be underestimated.} ({
The alternative} 16... cxd4 17. exd4 Nf4 {Grachev,B - Zubov,A Jerusalem 2015} {
doesn't seem to offer Black a comfortable play in view of} 18. Qh4 $1 $146 Nxd3
(18... Ne6 19. Rfe1 Rac8 20. Bf1 $14) 19. Nxd3 Ba6 20. Rfe1 Qd6 21. Nf4 $14 {
White's pieces are much more active, and the Pd5 is a cause of worries.}) 17.
Bc2 a6 18. Rfe1 {Obviously, now it is easier for White to take the upper hand
in the centre.} b5 19. a3 Rad8 ({In case of} 19... Bc6 20. e4 dxe4 21. d5 Bd7
22. d6 Qd8 23. Bxe4 $36 {the strong Pd6 offers White a powerful initiative.})
20. h3 $1 {The last preparations before occupying the centre - White prevents
any counter-attacking ideas with ...Ng4.} Qd7 21. e4 a5 22. e5 Ne8 {We have
been following the correspondence game Vassia, E - Manso Gil, A ICCF email 2015}
23. Qh4 $146 b4 ({The slower} 23... Bc6 {invites a bigger trouble:} 24. f4 b4
25. N3e2 $36 {the further f4-f5 advance will offer White a strong attack.}) 24.
Na4 $14 {White's knight will soon reach c5. Black's counter-play is
insufficient.} *

