 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4.
cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nge2 Nbd7 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8
11. f3 h6 {A double-edged decision: Black moves his Ph7 with a tempo, so the
Nf8 isn't tied with defending the pawn. On the downside, this move somewhat
weakens Black's k-side.} 12. Bh4 {This important position might arise with
various move orders since Black could have included ...h7-h6 earlier.} Ne6 {
The most common and consistent: Black involves his knight in fight over the
centre. On the other hand, it blocks the light-squared bishop.} ({The
developing move} 12... Bd7 {looks artificial as the Bd7 isn't placed well. It
allows White to immediately take the upper hand in the centre:} 13. e4 dxe4 14.
fxe4 Ne6 (14... Ng4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Rf3 $14) 15. h3 Nh5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17.
Rad1 $14 {White was better in Nenciulescu,S - Kraujunas,V ICCF email 2002}) (
12... c5 {was played by a few strong grandmasters, but it is dubious in view of}
13. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 14. dxc5 Rxe3 ({Hardly better is} 14... d4 15. Ne4 dxe3 16.
Rad1 Qe7 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Be4 $16 {Black's q-side is under strong pressure,
and the Pe3 feels very weak. Albrecht,R-Lehmann,M GER corr 1995}) 15. Rad1 {
The nasty opposition of Rd1 and Qd8 seems to pose Black serious problems.} Be6
({After} 15... d4 16. Be4 $1 {Black has nothing better than playing} Be6 {
with a transposition.}) 16. Be4 d4 17. Nb5 $16 {Black suffers material losses.
Bars,J - Efimov,A ICCF email 2015}) ({Another way of development} 12... Be6 13.
Rad1 Rc8 {doesn't really prevent White from playing ..e3-e4, but first it
makes sense to cover g4 with} 14. h3 $1 ({Premature is} 14. e4 dxe4 15. fxe4
Ng4 $132) 14... Nh5 ({After} 14... c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Nd4 $14 {the pinned
Nf6 makes it tougher to play with an isolated Pd5.}) 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. e4 $1 {
There is no reason for delaying this key move} dxe4 17. fxe4 c5 {Black has to
fight for control of e5} 18. Bb5 $1 {An important intermediate move.} Red8 19.
d5 Bxh3 {The best practical chance.} ({After} 19... Bd7 20. d6 Qe6 21. Rf5 {
White has nearly the decisive advantage due to his strong passer.}) 20. gxh3 a6
21. Bc4 b5 {We have been following the correspondence game Altrichter, U -
Rakay, K ICCF email 2014} {Black's hopes are connected with a trapped Bc4, but
after} 22. Rf5 $1 $146 Qh4 23. Kh2 bxc4 24. Rg1 {White has nearly the decisive
attack along the f and g files.}) (12... Nh5 $6 {In this redaction the
exchange of bishops definitely cannot be recommended as Blck struggles to
activate his Nh5.} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. e4 dxe4 15. fxe4 Qg5 16. Kh1 $16 {Black
was positionally busted, especially in view of coming ..e4-e5 and Ne4-d6.
Dobrov, V - Varley, P Caerleon 2006}) ({The fianchetto only partly solves
Black's problems with his q-side pieces:} 12... b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Kh1 {
I like this prophylactic move: it significantly increases the effect of e3-e4.}
Nh5 15. Bf2 Ne6 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in
Gholami Orimi, M - Tsaruk, M Konya 2018} {Among the other promising ways, I
mostly like} 16. Bh7+ $146 Kh8 17. Bf5 $36 {, and it's impossible to prevent
18.e4}) 13. Kh1 {This prophylactic move is always vital in such positions.
Obviously, after White plays e3-e4 it is safer to move the king from possible
threats along the diagonal.} ({The most popular} 13. Rad1 {also looks
attractive.}) 13... b6 {The most sensible response. Black makes the key c6-c5
break more attractive.} (13... Nh5 14. Bf2 Bd6 {, as in Sulypa,O - Kandic,M
Werther 1999} {can be strongly met with} 15. e4 $1 $146 Bc7 16. Qd2 {,
harmoniously placing all the pieces. I see nothing better for Black than
playing} Nhf4 17. Nxf4 Nxf4 18. Bc2 $16 {, and then Black's activity comes to
an end, while the strong pawn centre secures White a big positional advantage.}
) ({Black isn't optimally prepared for undermining the opponent's centre with} 
13... c5 $6 14. Bb5 $1 Bd7 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Rad1 $16 {The Pd5
was nearly lost in Bouget, A - Zhang, A Chess.com INT 2020}) 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Bf2
$1 {The Bh4 did its job, and now it comes back to cover e3 and fully
neutralize any Black's counterplay.} Rc8 ({As earlier,} 15... c5 {meets} 16.
Bb5 $1 Rf8 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Ng3 $36 {Velin Visuma,Y - Sarmiento Robles,P
Banos de Agua Santa 2020}) 16. e4 {Everything is ready for this move. All
White's pieces are getting activated now.} dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 {This is only a
temporary activity.} 18. Bg1 Bg5 19. e5 $16 {The strong central pawn chain
makes Black's position very cramped. Cvitan, O - Bex, P Biel 2005} *

