 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Nge2 Re8 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qc2
Nf8 11. f3 Be6 {This is the most popular continuation according to Mega
Databse, although it can be rarely seen on the high level nowadays. Black
overprotects d5 and connects his rook. On the downside, the be6 is placed
somewhat awkwardly as it blocks the e-file and can be attacked with Nf4.} 12.
Rad1 {A solid consolidating move. The opposition on the d-file makes the
possible e3-e4 much more attractive for white.} ({Premature is} 12. e4 dxe4 13.
fxe4 Ng4 $1 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Qd2 c5 16. d5 Bd7 {Black has stable control of
e5, so White hardly has anything special.}) 12... Rc8 {The opposition of Rc8
and White's queen might be promising for Black in the long run.} (12... Ng6 13.
Kh1 Rc8 {is another possible moves order.} ({Dubious is} 13... Qc7 $6 {,
making a threat of ...Ng4.} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. f4 $1 {Now the misplaced Be6
causes Black serious problems. For instance,} Bg4 16. Nxd5 $1 {Black was
already nearly lost in Albu,G - Pasti,A Arad 2019}) ({Hardly can be
recommended also} 13... Nh5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Black is ready to meet 15. e4 with
dxe4 and ...c6-c5, but after} 15. g4 $1 Nf6 16. Ng3 Nd7 17. Nf5 {He is rather
cramped. Garkauskas,O - Egoroff,J Foz do Iguacu 2013})) (12... N6d7 {In
general, the exchanges favour Black, who has less space. On the other hand, the
knight's placement isn't optimal now, so it is easier for White to take the
upper hand in the centre.} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. e4 {I see no reason for deviating
from this thematic advance.} dxe4 15. fxe4 Nb6 ({Even worse is} 15... Rac8 16.
Ng3 c5 17. d5 Bg4 18. Be2 $1 {By exchanging the bishops White vacates f5 for
his knight. This will support the strong Pd5. Black's position was nearly lost
in Janssen, R - Dambacher, M Hilversum 2007}) 16. e5 $1 {White unblocks the
b1-h7 diagonal and secures d6 outpost for his knight.} c5 17. Nb5 cxd4 18.
Nexd4 $36 {The activity of all White's pieces was threatening in Lobron, E -
Jussupow, A Amsterdam 1994}) 13. Kh1 {Another universal prophylactic move.
White avoids the possible checks along the a7-g1 diagonal.} ({As earlier,} 13.
e4 dxe4 14. fxe4 Ng4 {allows some activity for Black.}) 13... Ng6 ({Another
common option is} 13... a6 {with the idea to play ...c6-c5 at the proper moment
when b5 is covered.} 14. a3 {White also makes a vital move. Potentially, in
case of ...c6-c5 White could transfer his bishop to a2. Also, there is a
possibility to play the ''squeezing'' ..b2-b4.} b5 {This position occurred a few
times on the high level. Among White's players are Ivanchuk, Rodshtein and
others.} ({After} 14... N6d7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nf4 h6 17. Qf2 $36 {White is
perfectly prepared for pushing ..e3-e4, so Black is under strong pressure.
Navara,D - Malinovsky,K Ostrava 2017}) 15. Nf4 ({As earlier, after} 15. e4 dxe4
16. fxe4 Ng4 $1 17. Bc1 c5 {The active Ng4 offers Black a sufficient
counter-play.}) 15... h6 ({After} 15... Bd7 16. Qf2 h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. e4 $36
{White builds a strong attack on the k-side.}) 16. Bh4 N6d7 {This was
Rodshtein, M - Dervishi, E Baku 2016} {Now I mostly like the simple} 17. Bf2 $146
Nb6 18. e4 {White has a clear positional advantage due to strong pawns centre
and poor Nf8.}) 14. a3 Nd7 {Black is aiming to unblock the e-file to put more
pressure on the Pe3.} ({After} 14... Qc7 {White can claim the drawbacks of
queen's placement with} 15. Nf4 $1 Bd7 16. Qf2 {Now White's heavy pieces are
placed harmoniously, so the potential ..e3-e4 should be effective.} Rcd8 17.
Rc1 Qd6 18. Nxg6 hxg6 ({The anti-positional} 18... fxg6 $6 19. Bf4 Qe6 {
Ivanchuk,V - Bruzon Batista,L Merida 2006} {should be refuted by} 20. e4 $1
$146 dxe4 21. fxe4 Nh5 22. Be3 $16) 19. Bf4 Qe6 20. e4 dxe4 21. fxe4 $14 {
The pressure on the Pf7 and awkward placement of Qe6 make Black's position
unpleasant.}) ({In case of} 14... a6 {, preparing the freeing ...c6-c5 White
can switch to ''squeezing'' strategy with} 15. Na4 $5 Nd7 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. b4
$14 {There is no way to stop 18.Nc5, so Black is doomed to passive defence.
Sriram,J - Song,J Rennes 2009}) 15. Bxe7 (15. Bf4 $5 {, as was played by
Ivanchuk also comes to consideration.}) 15... Qxe7 16. Ng3 {A great spot for
the knight. It supports the key e3-e4 advance and can be relocated to f5 or h5.
} Nf6 {This position occurred in Hracek,Z - Caletka,R Czech Republic 2013} {
Here I suggest the following way to regroup the pieces:} 17. Qf2 $5 $146 {
White builds an attack along the f-file and overprotects d4 in advance.} Rcd8 (
{After} 17... c5 18. Bb1 cxd4 19. Rxd4 Ne5 20. Ba2 $14 {Black has no
sufficient counter-play, and the isolated Pd5 is a cause of worries.}) 18. h3 {
The g4-square is covered, so everything is ready for ..e3-e4.} c5 {Black more
or less has to play this.} 19. Bb1 b6 20. Rd2 $14 {White has a slight, but
long-lasting positional pressure: any time Black goes ...c5-c4 White will
always push e3-e4 with a great effect.} *

