 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4.
cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Nge2 Nbd7 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O {
This is the main tabia of Carlsbad with Nge2. The usual route of Nb8 is d7-f8/
g6 or e6, though there are also alternative directions.} Nf8 11. f3 g6 {
A speciality of Teimour Radjabov and other strong players. Black restricts the
opponent's light-squared bishop and vacates g7 for his pieces (mostly the
knight). On the downside, the dark squares around the king are permanently
exposed from now.} 12. Bh4 {The bishop hardly has better prospects than being
retreated to f2, so White does it in advance.} ({The most common alternative is
} 12. Rad1 Ne6 13. Bh4 {, when} b5 $5 14. Kh1 Bb7 {, followed by Rc8 and ...
c6-c5 was proved to be satisfactory for Black in many high-level games.}) 12...
Ne6 ({It makes a little sense to exchange the dark-squared bishop in the
following redaction:} 12... Nh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 {The Nh5 is misplaced, so White
can immediately take the upper hand in the centre:} 14. e4 dxe4 15. fxe4 Be6 {
This was Svetushkin, D - Balaskas, N Achaia 2017} {Not the simple} 16. Rf2 $146
Rad8 17. Raf1 $36 {would have put Black's king under serious pressure.}) (12...
b5 {This move makes more sense when Black's knight is still on d7 - in yields
Black the idea of ...Nb6-c4 or c6-c5.} 13. Bf2 {A standard approach: Since ..
e3-e4 traditionally provokes the nasty Nf6-g4 White moves his bishop back in
advance to cover d4 and e3.} Ne6 14. Kh1 Bb7 15. e4 {I see no reason for
delaying this thematic break, although 15.Rad1!? also makes sense.} b4 ({After
} 15... a6 16. Rad1 Rc8 {White can quickly extend in the centre with} 17. e5
Nh5 18. g4 $1 {Correctly not fearing of weakening the king.} Nhf4 19. Nxf4 Nxf4
20. Ne2 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 $14 {White has excellent prospects on the k-side: it
is only a matter of time before he will push f3-f4. At the same time, Black's
bishops are rather passive. Fessler,S - Ristea,T email 2019}) 16. Na4 Rc8 ({
I examined also} 16... dxe4 $146 17. fxe4 Rc8 {Black is now well prepared for
the key ...c6-c5 break but after} 18. Nc5 $1 Bxc5 19. dxc5 Ng4 20. Bc4 {
Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 17. e5 Nd7 18. f4 c5 19. Qd2 $14 {
The potential threat of ..f4-f5 put Black's king in serious danger in Debashis,
D - Panda,S Bhubaneswar 2019}) (12... Be6 {is inconsistent as e6 was the only
adequate square for the Nf8} 13. Kh1 Nh5 14. Bf2 Ng7 15. e4 {White was clearly
better due to his strong pawns centre. Reinderman,D -Hilarius,S Leiden 2007})
13. a4 $5 {A somewhat unusual move, that was only played a few times so far. It
is mainly aimed for preventing the standard counter-attacking measures with ...
b7-b5. Also, in some cases, White may consider the ''squeezing'' a4-a5.} Nh5 ({
The alternatives are:} 13... Bd7 14. Qd2 {the Qc2 did its job, so it makes
sense to take more control of e3 in light of further..e3-e4} Ng7 {This
position occurred in Bucsa, I - Lundberg, C ICCF email 2017. Black's obvious idea
is to exchange the light-squared bishop, but White shouldn't be worried about
it:} 15. Kh1 $146 Bf5 16. Bf2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 {Everything is ready for the
traditional extension in the centre.} Ne6 18. e4 $14 {A long struggle is
ahead when White's chances are preferable due to space advantage.}) (13... b6
{This move wasn't tried on practice, although I find it logical: Black vacates
b7 for his bishop and makes the potential ...c6-c5 more attractive.} 14. a5 b5
({After} 14... bxa5 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. Qxa5 Qb6 17. Rfb1 $14 {Black has no
compensation for his weaknesses.}) 15. Na2 $1 {White unblocks the c-file and
prepares the ''squeezing b2-b4.} Bd7 16. b4 {The move weakens c4, but Black's
knights are far away from it.} Rc8 17. Rae1 Ng7 18. Nec1 $14 {Black lacks
constructive ideas, while White can transfer his knight to c5 or push e3-e4 at
some point.}) 14. Bf2 {White has more space, so it makes sense to keep more
pieces on the board.} a5 {Black secures b4 for his pieces, but it isn't a big
achievement.} ({After} 14... Bd6 15. Kh1 Bc7 16. e4 Nef4 17. Nxf4 Nxf4 18. e5
$14 {The vulnerability of dark squares on the k-side starts to tell.}) 15. Rad1
Nc7 {it is a long way, but what else? The Ne6 is clearly misplaced.} 16. e4 Na6
17. Qd2 {Avoiding the exchange of Bd3 and moving the queen towards the k-side.}
Nb4 18. Bb1 $14 {The stable Nb4 doesn't fully compensate for White's pawn
centre and difficulties with developing the Bc8. Jumabayev,R - Yilmaz,M Moscow
2020} *

